text: The Northwoods sub-region can be immediately divided into northern and southern sections.
label: BODY

text: The upland forests of the northern section are characterized by potential dominance of shade-tolerant
label: BODY

text: species (primarily sugar maple, red maple, American beech, basswood, and eastern hemlock) on mesic
label: BODY

text: to dry mesic sites and by pines (jack, red, and eastern white), oaks (northern red, northern pin, and
label: BODY

text: white) and aspen (trembling and bigtooth) on drier, nutrient-poorer sites. Presence of any of the conifer
label: BODY

text: species in predominantly deciduous forest is another characteristic of the northern forest. There also are
label: BODY

text: extensive lowland forests dominated by coniferous (balsam fir, northern white cedar, black spruce and
label: BODY

text: tamarack) or deciduous species (black ash, red maple, balsam poplar).
label: BODY

text: The northern subsection is further characterized by an extensive cover of continuous forest with
label: BODY

text: relatively little fragmentation while the southern section is dominated by relatively small woodlots in
label: BODY

text: an agricultural matrix. Historically, the predominant agent of natural disturbance was wind in the north
label: BODY

text: The forest of the southern section is characterized by a predominance of oaks (primarily
label: BODY

text: northern red, white, black, bur) and a general absence of conifers. Many oak communities are fire-
label: BODY

text: dependent and, where seed sources exist, are now succeeding to shade tolerant species.
label: BODY

text: The Central Hardwoods sub-region can be divided into the glaciated area of northern Iowa,
label: BODY

text: Illinois, Indiana, and Ohio and the unglaciated southern portion of these states plus Kentucky. The
label: BODY

text: northern area has limited topographic relief and highly fragmented natural ecosystems due to past
label: BODY

text: clearing for agriculture. Further, the western portion of the glaciated area, from Iowa to western
label: BODY

text: Indiana, was historically a mixture of prairie and oak/hickory forest that was largely controlled by
label: BODY

text: Native Americans through the use fire. The southern unglaciated area, on the other hand, has greater
label: BODY

text: topographic relief and much greater forest cover than the northern area. The entire sub-region has been
label: BODY

text: heavily disturbed by human activities, which means that most of the existing forest stands date from
label: BODY

text: This sub-region has a great diversity of forest species that occur on sites ranging from dry to
label: BODY

text: wet. A typical woodland has 20 to 30 species of commercially important trees. Due to past
label: BODY

text: disturbances, most of the forests are currently dominated by seral species of oak and hickory with more
label: BODY

text: tolerant species of maple and beech in the sub-canopy. Many of the remaining old stands are dominated
label: BODY

text: by seral species, which probably reflect Native American activities that predate European occupation of
label: BODY

text: Species composition varies with site conditions. In the north, the relatively flat topography
label: BODY

text: generally has poor surface drainage so a typical woodland has such wet site species as bur oak, swamp
label: BODY

text: white oak, green ash, and red maple in depressional areas.  In contrast, better-drained soils in the same
label: BODY

text: woodland have northern red oak, white oak, white ash, American elm, and sugar maple as major
label: BODY

text: species. In the more hilly southern areas, the above species occur along with black oak, scarlet oak, and
label: BODY

text: chestnut oak on drier upper slope positions while yellow poplar becomes much more abundant on the
label: BODY

text: better sites of north facing slopes and in minor stream valleys. Major floodplains of the sub-region
label: BODY

text: generally have flood tolerant species, such as eastern cottonwood and silver maple.
label: BODY

text: Coniferous species are of minor importance in this sub-region. Eastern red cedar and Virginia
label: BODY

text: pine become more common in the southern areas. There are also a few relic stands of Northwoods
label: BODY

text: species, such as eastern white pine and eastern hemlock. In addition, species of southern pine and
label: BODY

text: eastern white pine have been widely planted to control erosion on disturbed lands.
